assistant: Unfortunately, as an AI language model, I am not able to access files. However, I can provide you with a code template for reading from one file and writing to another in C++:

```c++
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <string>

using namespace std;

int main() {
   string line;
   ifstream fin("file1.txt"); //opening file1 for reading

   if (fin.is_open()) { //checking if file is opened successfully
      ofstream fout("file2.txt"); //opening file2 for writing
      if (fout.is_open()) { //checking if file is opened successfully
         while (getline(fin, line)) { //reading each line from file1
            fout << line << endl; //writing each line to file2
         }
         fout.close(); //closing file2
      }
      else {
         cout << "Error: Unable to open file for writing." << endl;
      }
      fin.close(); //closing file1
   }
   else {
      cout << "Error: Unable to open file for reading." << endl;
   }

   return 0;
}
```

In this example, we first open `file1.txt` for reading using an `ifstream` object named `fin`. We then use a `while` loop and the `getline` function to read each line from `fin`, and write it to `file2.txt` using an `ofstream` object named `fout`.

As always, it is important to check if the files have been opened successfully before proceeding. If an error occurs, an appropriate message is displayed on the screen. Once we are done reading from and writing to the files, we close them using their respective `close` functions.

